Etymology 1[edit]

From Proto-Indo-European *kr-n-. Compare Old Irish caire (“sin”), Old English hierwan (“to moke”), Ancient Greek κάρνη (kárnē, “penalty”), Tocharian B karn- (“to vex”) and Lithuanian káirinti (“to provoke”)[1].

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈkaː.ri.noː/, [ˈkaː.ɾɪ.noː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈka.ri.no/, [ˈkaː.ri.nɔ]

Verb[edit]

cārinō (present infinitive cārināre, perfect active cārināvī, supine cārinātum); first conjugation

  1. I revile, I blame; I insult

Etymology 2[edit]

From carīna.

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /kaˈriː.noː/, [kaˈɾiː.noː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /kaˈri.no/, [kaˈriː.nɔ]

Verb[edit]

carīnō (present infinitive carīnāre, perfect active carīnāvī, supine carīnātum); first conjugation

  1. I supply with a shell

Etymology 3[edit]

Adjective[edit]

carinō

  1. dative masculine singular of carinus
  2. dative neuter singular of carinus
  3. ablative masculine singular of carinus
  4. ablative neuter singular of carinus
